content.description: Sustained climbing on perfect rock to about half way where it eases off to the anchor shared with Grasshole.
content.location: Scramble up to a platform on the the far left side of Fly Dog. Grasshole climbs up the corner and Lands End is the bolt line to the left.

content.description: Starts with a finger crack for 15 ft. then follows nice crimps and ledges with several bolts to the roof. A convenient knee bar here allows you to get 2 .75 or 1" cams in the roof, then cast off with tight hand jams and tricky foot work. The crux is getting over the lip. Pictured here, Randy got the moves.
content.protection: app. 3 bolts, cams .2-1"   Bolted rap anchor on top.
content.location: In the middle of the wall, right below the objective, the obvious roof splitter. The whole roof section appears to be detached from the main wall but is so huge that it probably is locked in place. Just a heads up.

content.description: Steep start for several bolts to the crux, then backs off a bit to the anchor.
content.location: This is the last possible route on the Fly Dog thus the name. Just to the left of Stand your Ground.

content.description: Really nice face climbing on stellar rock. Starts in a steep right facing corner with several bolts, the slab above not yet visible. Once onto the slab there are nice cutters and edges continuing along the arete to the anchor.
content.location: Right side of formation, scramble up a gully with some bushes to the base of this slab. There is an alternative TR start to the right following a weakness which about .10c

content.description:
Start in a corner with some laybacking/stemming. Place a #2 before pulling over a large block, and then head up the slab. A fun final mantle gets you to the anchors.

Beware of friable rock in the corner. Water can seep through the crack quite profusely.
content.location: From Fly Dog, walk further uphill and left. You'll pass an overhang and find Grasshole in the next corner, with two more bolted lines to its left.

content.description:
A moderate outing up the cleanest rock to the top of the formation.

Save me a thousand words and look at my paint by numbers photo of the crag to locate the start of the route.

Bolts off the ground protect the 5.9 crux getting into the crack. When the crack jogs hard left, head right across the slab to the bolted anchor on the white tombstone above. Climb straight over this anchor to another pair of bolts 20' higher up the slab, belay here.

Pitch 2: Head up left off the belay into the chimney-ish slot. Continue up the slab above to the summit in a long 200' stretch, or stop and belay again at the two bolt rap station you'll pass on your left.

Descent is via 4, ~75' rappels.  Rap to the station you just passed, and again to another one left of the route (Reef Bounce anchor.) Rap again to the Threat Arete anchor, and once again to the ground.
Start on some blocky ledges past several bolts and gear and move left to the perfect hand crack. Take this to a bolt anchor.
content.location: If you look up and follow the large angling roof to its left end, right below is the start of the route.

content.description:
Just to the right of

Fly Dog

sits this clean corner.  Follow it as it trends to the right and head straight up the slab as the corner fades away to the right.  Bolted anchor/rap station.

Warm, bakey days will have you dreaming of the stream that flows nearby during wet winters.
content.protection: About a half a dozen bolts and single cams from fingers to thin hands.

content.description: From the upper ledge start your traverse right with increasing difficulty. Hard clips around the corner where a small incut provides the only foothold (sometimes wet). The handholds get better but the pump is now setting in so you better keep moving. The upper crack is easy enough to the anchor.
content.location: Starts the same as Grasshole but follows the seam going right around the bulge to a vertical crack.
